const a = [
  {"id":9508,"text":"What is the drug of choice in cestode infection?","explanation":null,"reference":"Katzung BG, ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 944.","responses":[{"text":"Ivermectin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyrantel pamoate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albendazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Praziquantel","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diethylcarbamazine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10161,"text":"Which of the following drug is the preferable treatment in the case of neurocysticercosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Katzung BG, ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 940, 945.","responses":[{"text":"Praziquantel","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyrantel pamoate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albendazole","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ivermectin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mebendazaole","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10363,"text":"Which of the following is an appropriate drug in the treatment of acute enteric fever?","explanation":null,"reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 260-261.","responses":[{"text":"Ceftriaxone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sulphonamide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chloramphenicol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amoxicillin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ampicillin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20164,"text":"The district government of a certain city is trying to control a malaria epidemic. For this purpose, they want to initiate the strategy of vector control. They launch the distribution of insecticide-treated nets (ITNs) to households. Which of the following captures the other core intervention that must be used for effective vector control?","explanation":"**Indoor residual spraying** (IRS) involves the application of insecticides to the interior walls and surfaces of houses. This method targets the malaria-carrying mosquitoes when they come into contact with the treated surfaces indoors. IRS is a core intervention for effective vector control alongside ITNs.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile malaria vaccines have been developed, they are not the primary vector control strategy. Malaria vaccines primarily aim to provide immunity against the *Plasmodium* parasite, rather than targeting the mosquito vectors directly.\r\n\r\nProphylaxis typically refers to the use of preventive measures, such as medications, to protect individuals from developing a disease. While it can be used for malaria prevention, it is not the core intervention for vector control.\r\n\r\nSurveillance involves monitoring and tracking the spread of diseases, including malaria. While surveillance is crucial for understanding the disease's prevalence and distribution, it is not a direct intervention for vector control.\r\n\r\nPreventive chemotherapies may include the use of antimalarial medications as a preventive measure for individuals at high risk of malaria. While this is an important strategy, it is not the primary vector control method.","reference":"Dow lecture slides. Infectious module. Subject: Community Medicine, Topic: Malaria, Sub-topic: Vector control.","responses":[{"text":"Vaccine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Surveillance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Preventive chemotherapies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Indoor residual spraying (IRS)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prophylaxis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20165,"text":"A physician is interested in performing entomological testing on the mosquito which is an important vector for transmitting viral fevers in Pakistan. Which of the following mosquitoes is of interest to him?","explanation":"***Aedes aegypti*** is a primary vector for the transmission of several viral fevers, including dengue, chikungunya, yellow fever, and Zika virus. In regions like **Pakistan**, where dengue and chikungunya are prevalent, *Aedes aegypti* plays a significant role in the transmission of these diseases. This mosquito species is well-adapted to urban environments and breeds in artificial water containers, making it a common vector in populated areas.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n*Aedes triseriatus* (eastern treehole mosquito) is primarily known for transmitting the La Crosse encephalitis virus in the United States.\r\n\r\n*Culiseta mosquito* species are generally cold-climate mosquitoes and are not major vectors for the viral diseases commonly found in Pakistan.\r\n\r\n*Anopheles stephensi* is mainly known as a vector for malaria, not for viral fevers like dengue or chikungunya.\r\n\r\n*Culex mosquito* species are vectors for West Nile virus, Japanese encephalitis, and filariasis, but they are not the primary vectors for dengue or chikungunya, which are more prevalent in Pakistan.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 243.","responses":[{"text":"Anopheles stephensi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aedes aegypti","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aedes triseriatus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Culiseta mosquito","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Culex mosquito","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20166,"text":"A non-governmental organization working to control malaria in flood-affected areas of Pakistan seeks advice from a public health specialist regarding the control and elimination of malaria. Which one of the following options captures the most appropriate advice?","explanation":"**Vector control** encompasses various strategies to reduce the population of malaria-transmitting mosquitoes. These strategies can include the use of bed nets, insecticide spraying, larval control, and environmental management. Given the context of controlling malaria in flood-affected areas, vector control would be the most appropriate advice as it addresses the source of **transmission**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nSurveillance is essential for monitoring and tracking the spread of malaria. While it is crucial, it is typically part of a broader malaria control program rather than standalone advice.\r\n\r\nMalaria vaccines have been developed, but their availability and effectiveness vary. A vaccine may be a part of malaria control efforts, but it might not be the most immediate advice, especially considering the context of flood-affected areas where rapid intervention is needed.\r\n\r\nPreventive chemotherapies involve the administration of antimalarial drugs to at-risk populations, such as pregnant women or children. While important, it is typically a component of a comprehensive malaria control program.\r\n\r\nDichloro-diphenyl-trichloroethane (DDT)  a pesticide used for indoor residual spraying to control mosquito vectors that transmit malaria. While it can be effective, it may not always be the most appropriate advice, especially considering potential environmental and health concerns associated with DDT usage.","reference":"Dow lecture slides. Infectious module. Subject: Community Medicine, Topic: Malaria, Sub-topic: Vector Control.","responses":[{"text":"Preventive chemotherapies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vaccine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"DDT spraying","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Surveillance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vector control","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21016,"text":"A patient presents to the outpatient department with a history of cough for more than three weeks, night sweats, loss of appetite, and fever. The physician advises a chest x-ray, sputum culture, and Zeihl-nelson staining of the sputum. He was diagnosed as a case of tuberculosis. Which one of the following is an identifying feature of tuberculosis?","explanation":"One of the hallmark features of tuberculosis is the formation of **granulomas**. Granulomas are organized collections of immune cells, primarily macrophages, that surround and contain the ***Mycobacterium tuberculosis*** bacteria.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nTuberculosis is not typically associated with the constriction of blood vessels.\r\n\r\nWhile tuberculosis can lead to pleural effusion in some cases (the collection of serous fluid in the pleural cavity around the lungs), this is not the defining feature of tuberculosis.\r\n\r\nTuberculosis does involve the infiltration of immune cells, including monocytes and macrophages, into the affected tissue. However, granuloma formation is a more specific and distinguishing feature of tuberculosis.\r\n\r\nTuberculosis does lead to the accumulation of macrophages at the site of infection. However, this is not specific to tuberculosis.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 588.","responses":[{"text":"Accumulation of macrophges","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Constriction of blood vessels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Granuloma formation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Collection of serous fluid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infiltration of monocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21017,"text":"The journey of leukocytes from the vessel lumen to the tissue is a multi-step process mediated and controlled by adhesion molecules and cytokines called chemokines. Which one of the following statements is correct regarding sequential phases?","explanation":"The leukocytes initially roll along the endothelium (**rolling**), then marginate towards the endothelial surface (**margination**), and finally adhere to the endothelium (**adhesion**). This presents the correct sequential phases in the correct order.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 77.","responses":[{"text":"Adhesion, margination, and rolling to endothelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Margination, adhesion, and rolling to endothelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Margination inside the endothelium and vessel wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Margination in a tissue towards a chemotactic stimulus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rolling, margination, and adhesion to endothelium","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21018,"text":"A 3-year-old unvaccinated girl is brought to the outpatient department with fever, cough, runny nose, and watery eyes for 3 days. On physical examination, there is a maculopapular rash on the face, neck, and trunk. Her elder sibling has a history of similar complaints from 1 week ago. What is the most probable diagnosis?","explanation":"**Measles**, also known as rubeola, is characterized by symptoms such as fever, cough, runny nose, and conjunctivitis (watery eyes). A distinctive feature of measles is the presence of a **maculopapular rash** that typically starts on the face and spreads to the trunk and extremities.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHerpes simplex virus can cause oral or genital ulcers.\r\n\r\nVaricella zoster virus causes chickenpox, which is characterized by an itchy vesicular rash.\r\n\r\nRubella, also known as German measles, can cause a rash similar to measles, but it is usually milder and less extensive. Given the sibling's history and the characteristic rash, measles is a more likely diagnosis than rubella.\r\n\r\nKawasaki disease primarily presents with fever, conjunctival injection, changes in the oral mucosa, rash, extremity changes, and cervical lymphadenopathy. While it can include rash and fever, the presentation is distinct from what is described in this case.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 236.","responses":[{"text":"Measles","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Varicella zoster","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Herpes simplex virus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rubella","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kawasaki diseases","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21019,"text":"A 6-year-old boy is brought to the outpatient department with complaints of high-grade fever (102°F) for 4 days. On physical examination, the child is febrile with cropped vesicles on the trunk and scattered scabbed lesions. Which of the following infections is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"Varicella virus, which causes chickenpox, fits the clinical picture described. Chickenpox is characterized by a high-grade fever and the development of vesicles on the trunk and other parts of the body. The vesicles eventually scab over.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nCytomegalovirus virus is not commonly associated with a high-grade fever and vesicular rash.\r\n\r\nRubella is known for causing a fine, pink rash that starts on the face and spreads to the trunk and extremities.\r\n\r\nMeasles is associated with a characteristic red, blotchy rash.\r\n\r\nEnterovirus infections do not typically present with the specific pattern of vesicles and scabbed lesions described in the case.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 238.","responses":[{"text":"Enterovirus virus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytomegalovirus virus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rubella virus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Measles virus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Varicella virus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21020,"text":"A 40-year-old female presents with complaints of purulent vaginal discharge and intermenstrual bleeding. Gram staining of endocervical screening revealed the presence of gram-negative diplococci. What would be the diagnosis?","explanation":"***Neisseria gonorrhoeae*** is a gram-negative diplococcus and is known to cause gonorrhea, a sexually transmitted infection that can result in purulent vaginal discharge and intermenstrual bleeding. The presence of gram-negative diplococci on Gram staining is characteristic of *N. gonorrhoeae*, making it the likely culprit in this case.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n*Chlamydia trachomatis* is not associated with gram-negative diplococci but rather with intracellular inclusion bodies.\r\n\r\n*Haemophilus ducreyi* causes chancroid, characterized by genital ulcers, not vaginal discharge.\r\n\r\nHerpes simplex virus (HSV) can cause genital herpes, leading to painful genital ulcers rather than vaginal discharge.\r\n\r\n*Trichomonas vaginalis* is a protozoan parasite responsible for trichomoniasis, which can cause vaginal discharge, but it does not appear as gram-negative diplococci on Gram staining.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 339-340.","responses":[{"text":"Trichomonas vaginalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Herpex simplex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neisseria gonorrhoeae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilus ducreyi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlamydiae trachomatis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21021,"text":"A young man presented to the emergency room with a history of high-grade fever\r\nassociated with chills and rigors. He lives in an area of poor sanitation, streets with stagnant water, insects, and mosquitoes. A complete blood count (CBC) examination of blood from the patient revealed distorted RBCs, double in size, and Schüffner's dots. What is the causative agent?","explanation":"High-grade fever with chills and rigors is typical of malaria, a disease commonly transmitted in regions with poor sanitation and stagnant water, which are breeding grounds for mosquitoes, the vectors for malaria.\r\n\r\n**Schüffner dots** are fine, granular, red to orange dots seen in the RBCs infected with *P. vivax* or *P. ovale*. However, the mention of the **RBCs** being double in **size** is more specific to ***P. vivax*** infection.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nPlasmodium malariae* typically causes quartan malaria, with fever spikes every third day. It does not cause enlarged RBCs or Schüffner dots.\r\n\r\n*Plasmodium knowlesi* is a less common cause of malaria and can cause severe disease. It does not typically present with the specific RBC changes seen in *P. vivax* infection.\r\n\r\n*Plasmodium falciparum* is known for causing severe malaria and cerebral involvement. The blood smear in *P. falciparum* infection shows multiple ring forms and Maurer's dots, not Schüffner's dots or enlarged RBCs.\r\n\r\n*Plasmodium ovale* can also cause enlarged RBCs with Schüffner's dots, but it is less common than *P. vivax* and typically causes mild disease. The mention of RBCs being double in size is more specific to *P. vivax*.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 275-276.","responses":[{"text":"Plasmodium knowlesi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmodium falciparum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmodium ovale","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmodium malariae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmodium vivax","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21022,"text":"Once the fusion of HIV takes place with the host cell, viral RNA is released into the cytoplasm. Viral RNA is then used to synthesize dsDNA by which of the following enzymes?","explanation":"**Reverse transcriptase** is the enzyme responsible for synthesizing dsDNA from viral RNA in the context of HIV replication. This process is crucial for the retroviral life cycle, and reverse transcriptase plays a central role in converting the viral RNA genome into dsDNA, which can then integrate into the host cell's genome.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nLigase is an enzyme that joins two strands of DNA together by catalyzing the formation of phosphodiester bonds between them.\r\n\r\nHelicase is an enzyme that unwinds double-stranded DNA, separating the two strands to allow other enzymes to access the DNA.\r\n\r\nProtease is an enzyme responsible for cleaving viral polyproteins into functional proteins during the final stages of the HIV life cycle.\r\n\r\nIntegrase is an enzyme responsible for integrating the synthesized dsDNA into the host cell's genome, but it is not involved in the initial step of synthesizing dsDNA from viral RNA.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 250.","responses":[{"text":"Ligase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Protease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Helicase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reverse transcriptase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Integrase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21023,"text":"HIV uses a CD4⁺ molecule as a receptor, which is present in CD4⁺ cells such as T-lymphocytes, macrophages, monocytes, dendritic cells other and antigen-presenting cells. Virus entry into the human cell is mediated by which of the following proteins?","explanation":"**Gp120** and **gp41** are the viral envelope glycoproteins of **HIV** that are directly involved in mediating virus entry into host cells. gp120 binds to the CD4⁺ receptor on the surface of T-lymphocytes, macrophages, monocytes, dendritic cells, and antigen-presenting cells. This binding triggers conformational changes in gp120 and exposes gp41, which then facilitates the fusion of the viral and host cell membranes, allowing HIV to **enter the host cell**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nP24 antigen is a viral protein used for diagnostic purposes in detecting HIV infection, but it is not involved in the entry of the virus into human cells.\r\n\r\nVpr is an accessory protein of HIV that plays a role in several functions, including cell cycle regulation, but it is not directly involved in virus entry.\r\n\r\nVif is another accessory protein of HIV that helps the virus evade the host's immune defenses by targeting certain cellular proteins, but it is not responsible for virus entry.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 249-250.","responses":[{"text":"Vpr","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"P24 antigen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vif","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"gp120 and gp41","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"P9 gag","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21024,"text":"Malaria is an intermittent and remittent fever caused by a protozoan parasite that invades the red blood cells and is transmitted by mosquitoes in many tropical and subtropical regions. Anopheles mosquito takes a blood meal from humans and injects which of the forms of plasmodium parasite?","explanation":"**Sporozoite** is the form of the *Plasmodium* parasite that is injected into the human host by *Anopheles* mosquitoes. These sporozoites are present in the mosquito's salivary glands and are transmitted when the mosquito takes a blood meal. Once inside the human body, sporozoites travel to the liver and infect hepatocytes, initiating the malaria infection.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHypnozoites are dormant forms associated with relapsing malaria, not injected by mosquitoes.\r\n\r\nSchizonts represent a stage within infected red blood cells.\r\n\r\nWhile gametocytes play a role in the mosquito's gut, they are not the initial form injected into humans.\r\n\r\nMerozoites are released from infected red blood cells.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 273.","responses":[{"text":"Gametocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Merozoites","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shizont","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypnozoites","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sporozoite","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21025,"text":"Balanced infection control practices (ICP) can save hospitals a considerable amount of money, e.g., an outbreak of GNR can be controlled effectively by hand hygiene rather than prescribing expensive antibiotics. \"The first requirement in a hospital is that it should do the sick no harm.\" Who said the above words?","explanation":"The quote \"The first requirement in a hospital is that it should do the sick no harm\" is attributed to **Florence Nightingale**. Florence Nightingale was a pioneering nurse known for her contributions to modern nursing practices and her emphasis on hygiene and infection control in healthcare settings.","reference":"Communications WH. A nurse’s determination to “do the sick no harm” – achieving interoperability inside of the hospital - westhealth. Org. Accessed November 14, 2023.","responses":[{"text":"Willam","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Florence Nightingale","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ogston","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colbrook","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lister","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21027,"text":"A young child presented to the outpatient department with a history of low-grade fever, loss of appetite, and lethargy. Blood culture is positive for Salmonella typhi. Salmonella typhi is transmitted by which of the following routes?","explanation":"***Salmonella typhi***, the bacterium responsible for causing typhoid fever, is primarily transmitted through the **oral-fecal route**. Typhoid fever is typically contracted by consuming food or water contaminated with feces containing Salmonella typhi. This contamination can occur due to poor sanitation practices or improper handling of food and water.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 791.","responses":[{"text":"Oral fecal route","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Skin penetration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhalation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sexual route","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood transfusion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21028,"text":"A 24-year-old male patient presents with pain in his left knee and a burning sensation during urination. On examination, he has noticeable conjunctival inflammation. He denies any recent gastroenteritis but has had several sexual partners and has not always used protection. Which organism is most likely responsible for his presentation?","explanation":"The patient's history of multiple sexual partners and inconsistent use of protection puts him at a higher risk for sexually transmitted infections, including gonorrhea, and chlamydia trichomatis. \r\n\r\n***Chlamydia trichomatis*** is a bacterium responsible for Chlamydia, a sexually transmitted infection (STI). It is usually associated with Reiter's syndrome, a combination of urethritis, conjunctivitis, and arthritis. Arthritis can be of sacroiliac or the knee joint. \r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n*Treponema pallidum* is the bacterium responsible for syphilis.\r\n\r\n*Neisseria Gonorrhea* is a common cause of urethritis, however, conjunctivitis is an uncommon complication. In some cases, untreated gonorrhea can lead to disseminated gonococcal infection  (DGI). DGI can cause symptoms in other parts of the body, including joints. This is known as gonococcal arthritis, which can affect the knee and cause joint pain. However, DGI is a rare complication and is typically seen in women, not in men. This patient has a more consistent presentation with Reiter syndrome possibly caused by *Chlamydia trichomatis*.\r\n\r\n*Mycoplasma genitalium* is associated with urethritis and other genital infections but is less commonly associated with joint pain or conjunctivitis.\r\n\r\n*Trichomonas vaginalis* is a parasite that causes trichomoniasis, a sexually transmitted infection. While it can cause genital symptoms, it is not typically associated with joint pain or conjunctivitis.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 340-341\r\nDow Lecture slides: Infectious Diseases Module, Microbiology slides, Topic: Micro-organisms causing sexually transmitted diseases","responses":[{"text":"Chlamydia trachomatis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Treponema pallidum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mycoplasma genitalium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neisseria gonorrhoea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trichomalis vaginalis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21029,"text":"A 33-year-old woman presents to the outpatient department with a three-day history of a white, fishy vaginal discharge. She has no history of sexually transmitted disease, post-coital bleeding, or dysuria. On speculum examination, there is a milky fluid in the posterior fornix but no signs of inflammation. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Bacterial vaginosis** (BV) is characterized by a white or grayish vaginal discharge with a fishy odor, especially after sexual intercourse. It typically does not cause inflammation or itching. On speculum examination, a clue cell pattern may be observed in the vaginal discharge, which is a key diagnostic feature of BV.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nCandidiasis typically presents with itching and a thick, cottage cheese-like vaginal discharge. It is not associated with a fishy odor.\r\n\r\n*Neisseria gonorrhoeae* is a bacterium that can cause gonorrhea, which often presents with symptoms such as dysuria (painful urination) and yellow or greenish discharge.\r\n\r\nDonovanosis is a sexually transmitted infection caused by *Klebsiella granulomatis*. It presents with painless genital ulcers or nodules.\r\n\r\nChlamydia can cause a variety of symptoms, including vaginal discharge, but it is often associated with dysuria and can lead to complications if left untreated.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 988.","responses":[{"text":"Chlamydia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neisseria gonorrhoea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Donovanosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Candidiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacterial vaginosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22047,"text":"What are the four rules of professional-patient relationships set forth and explained by Beauchamp and Childress?","explanation":"The four rules of professional-patient relationships set forth by Beauchamp and Childress are outlined below.\r\n\r\n**Autonomy**: This rule emphasizes respect for the patient's right to make their own decisions about their medical treatment and care. Healthcare professionals should provide patients with the information and support needed to make informed choices and should respect those choices, even if they differ from the healthcare provider's recommendations.\r\n\r\n**Non-maleficence**: This rule entails the principle of \"do no harm.\" Healthcare professionals have a duty to avoid causing harm to their patients. This includes minimizing risks and ensuring that the potential benefits of any treatment or intervention outweigh the potential harms.\r\n\r\n**Beneficence**: Beneficence requires healthcare providers to act in the best interests of their patients. They should seek to promote the well-being of their patients and provide care that maximizes benefits while minimizing harm.\r\n\r\n**Justice**: The principle of justice focuses on the fair distribution of healthcare resources and the equitable treatment of patients. Healthcare professionals should ensure that all patients have equal access to care and that there is no discrimination in the provision of healthcare services.","reference":"Page K. The four principles: Can they be measured and do they predict ethical decision making? BMC Med Ethics. 2012;13:10. doi:10.1186/1472-6939-13-10","responses":[{"text":"Respect for autonomy, non-maleficence, beneficence, and justice","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Autonomy, non-maleficence, equality, and justice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autonomy, privacy, respect, and confidentiality","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autonomy, privacy, respect, and secrecy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Veracity, privacy, beneficence, and non-maleficence","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22048,"text":"What is the concept of justice in ethics?","explanation":"\"Health resources must be distributed according to the principles of equity.\" This statement reflects the concept of justice in medical ethics. It emphasizes the fair and equitable distribution of healthcare resources, ensuring that all individuals have access to necessary medical care without discrimination or undue advantage to certain groups. This principle is often associated with distributive justice, which seeks to minimize healthcare disparities and promote fairness in resource allocation.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nTo keep the secrecy of the patient relates more to the principle of confidentiality rather than justice in ethics. It pertains to the patient's right to privacy and the duty of healthcare professionals to protect their medical information.\r\n\r\nEthical principles often focus on the responsibilities and obligations of healthcare professionals rather than patients to society.\r\n\r\nThe patient's right to choose or refuse treatment relates to the principle of autonomy, where patients have the right to make decisions about their medical care.\r\n\r\nBeneficence emphasizes the duty of healthcare professionals to act in the best interests of their patients.","reference":"Olejarczyk JP, Young M. Patient rights and ethics. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed November 10, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538279/","responses":[{"text":"Taken as patients right to choose or refuse treatment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"An obligation of the patient to the society","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To keep the secrecy of patient","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Health resources must be distributed according to the principals of equity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"For medical professionals to do good for all patients under all circumstances","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22049,"text":"Regarding expressed oral consent, which of the following statements is correct?","explanation":"Expressed oral consent is often taken for minor medical procedures where the risks are low, and the patient is fully conscious and able to understand and agree to the procedure verbally.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nExpressed oral consent does not require signatures from either the doctor or the patient. It is a verbal acknowledgment of the patient's willingness to undergo a procedure.\r\n\r\nExpressed oral consent can be taken in various medical situations, not limited to emergencies. It is commonly used in minor procedures or treatments where written consent may not be necessary.\r\n\r\nExpressed oral consent cannot be taken from unconscious patients, as they are unable to provide verbal consent. In such cases, medical professionals may rely on implied consent or seek consent from a legal guardian or next of kin if available.","reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed. CBS Publishers; 2019: 31-32.","responses":[{"text":"It should be signed by both, doctor as well as patient","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is taken in minor procedures","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It should be signed by the patient only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Only taken in emergencies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is taken for unconscious patients","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22050,"text":"In which of the following circumstances can confidentiality be breached?","explanation":"Patient confidentiality is a fundamental principle in healthcare, but it can be breached when the patient provides explicit, informed consent to share their medical information with specific individuals or entities. In such cases, healthcare providers can disclose information as authorized by the patient.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nEconomic factors or non-compliance with treatment plans should not lead to a breach of patient confidentiality. Healthcare providers are obligated to prioritize patient privacy and confidentiality regardless of resource limitations or patient behaviors.\r\n\r\nThe need for invasive treatment does not justify the breach of patient confidentiality. Invasive treatments may require informed consent and discussions with the patient, but patient confidentiality remains protected.\r\n\r\nLawyers may request medical records or information related to a patient's condition, but healthcare providers should follow legal and ethical guidelines for releasing patient information. The release of medical information to legal entities typically requires patient consent or compliance with applicable laws and regulations governing such disclosures.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 8.","responses":[{"text":"When lawyer need information","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"When financial resources are scarce and patient is not compliant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"For a patient who requires invasive treatment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"When a patient authorizes to do so","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"When the patient does not listen to the doctor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22052,"text":"Transplantation terminology contains terms to describe the relationship of the graft donor to the graft recipient. Which of the following is the correct terminology for a graft between genetically non-identical members of the same species?","explanation":"An allogeneic graft involves the transplantation of tissues or organs between genetically non-identical members of the same species. Most organ and tissue transplants are allogeneic.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAutogenic graft refers to a graft transplanted from one site to another on the same individual.\r\n\r\nAn isogeneic graft refers to a graft between genetically identical individuals, typically monozygotic twins.\r\n\r\nA xenogeneic graft involves the transplantation of tissues or organs between different species.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 128.","responses":[{"text":"Allogeneic graft","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Autogenic graft","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Xenogeneic graft","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Halogenic graft","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isogeneic graft","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22053,"text":"In a court of law, leading questions are permitted exclusively during cross-examination. What is the only other circumstance in which the prosecution can pose leading questions?","explanation":"When a witness is declared hostile, **leading questions** are allowed to be used by the examining attorney. This allows the attorney to elicit information from a **witness** who is uncooperative or **hostile**, as the witness may be biased or unwilling to provide truthful or complete answers.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nLeading questions are typically not used during the direct examination of expert witnesses, including chemical examiners, as they are expected to provide their expert opinions without leading questions.\r\n\r\nPrivileged communication involves situations where certain communications are protected by law (e.g., attorney-client privilege, doctor-patient privilege). Leading questions are not used in these contexts as the goal is to protect the confidentiality of the communication.\r\n\r\nLeading questions are not used when a witness is voluntarily providing information during direct examination. In such cases, open-ended questions are often used to allow the witness to freely provide their account of events.\r\n\r\nRe-examination typically involves clarifying or addressing points that arose during cross-examination. Leading questions are generally not used during re-examination, as it is intended to be non-leading and focused on specific issues that arose during the cross-examination.","reference":"Subrahmanyam, B. V. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed., CBS Publishers, 2019: 11.","responses":[{"text":"Chemical examiner's testimony","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Witness declared hostile","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Re-examination","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Volunteering a statement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Privileged communication","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22055,"text":"Which of the following terms describes all legal means that help a fact, the truth of which is submitted in judicial proceedings?","explanation":"In a court of law, **evidence** is any information, objects, documents, or testimony presented to establish the truth or validity of a fact in a case. Evidence can take various forms, including affidavits, testimonies, depositions, documents, and more. It plays a crucial role in helping the court make informed decisions based on the facts and circumstances presented during judicial proceedings.","reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed. CBS Publishers; 2019: 16.","responses":[{"text":"Deposition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Summon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Evidence","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Affidavit","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Testimony","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22056,"text":"An injured person with a broken leg was being transported to the hospital in an ambulance. At a signal crossing, suddenly another vehicle collided with the ambulance resulting in the death of the injured person. What legal principle or concept is most applicable to this scenario?","explanation":"**Novus actus interveniens** refers to a new intervening act that breaks the chain of causation, relieving the original party from liability. In this scenario, the collision with another vehicle could be considered a new intervening act that broke the causal link between the initial injury and the death of the injured person, potentially absolving the ambulance personnel from liability for the death.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nVicarious liability holds one party responsible for the actions of another, such as an employer being held liable for the actions of their employee.\r\n\r\nRes ipsa loquitur is a legal doctrine that allows the inference of negligence based on the circumstances of an event.\r\n\r\nContributory negligence occurs when the injured party's actions also contribute to the harm they suffered.","reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed. CBS Publishers; 2019: 43.","responses":[{"text":"Res ipsa loquitur","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Novus actus interveniens","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Confounding negligence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vicarious liability","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contributory negligence","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22061,"text":"The parents presented a 3-year-old female child to the outpatient department with a one-week history of fever and cough, accompanied by conjunctivitis and coryza for the past three days. Notably, the child's elder brother experienced a similar condition characterized by a maculopapular rash all over his body two weeks ago. What is the likely problem with this child?","explanation":"**Measles** is a highly contagious viral infection caused by the measles virus. It typically presents with symptoms like fever, cough, conjunctivitis, and inflammation of the mucous membranes of the nose (coryza). After a few days of these initial symptoms, a characteristic **maculopapular rash** usually appears.\r\n\r\nMeasles is known for its person-to-person transmission, and close contacts, especially family members, are at high risk of contracting the virus.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile viral conjunctivitis can cause conjunctival redness and discharge, it usually does not present with the combination of fever, cough, coryza, and a history of a maculopapular rash in a close contact.\r\n\r\nUpper respiratory tract infection and lower respiratory tract infection are general terms that describe infections of the respiratory system. However, the specific symptoms and history mentioned (fever, cough, conjunctivitis, coryza, and a rash in the sibling) are more indicative of measles.\r\n\r\nChickenpox typically presents with a pruritic vesicular rash rather than a maculopapular rash.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 350.","responses":[{"text":"Upper respiratory tract infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chickenpox","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Viral conjunctivitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lower respiratory tract infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Measles","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22064,"text":"The parents brought a 10-year-old male child with a history of fever for 10 days. On examination, the child appears sick, febrile, and toxic. What is the gold standard test for diagnosis?","explanation":"**Blood culture and sensitivity** is the gold standard test for diagnosing **typhoid fever**. It involves taking a blood sample from the patient and culturing it in a suitable medium to detect the presence of *Salmonella typhi*. Sensitivity testing can help determine the most effective antibiotic treatment.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile a CBC can provide valuable information about white blood cell counts and differential counts, it is not the gold standard test for diagnosing typhoid fever. A CBC may show leukopenia (low white blood cell count) and relative lymphocytosis, but it is not specific to typhoid fever.\r\n\r\nThe Typhi dot test is an immunochromatographic assay used to detect antibodies against *Salmonella typhi* in the blood. It can provide rapid results and may be used as an initial screening test, but confirmation usually requires a blood culture.\r\n\r\nThe Widal test measures antibody titers against specific antigens of *Salmonella typhi*. While it has been used historically for typhoid fever diagnosis, it has limitations and is not considered the gold standard due to issues with false-positive and false-negative results.\r\n\r\nPCR-based assays can detect the DNA of *Salmonella typhi* in blood, making them highly sensitive and specific for diagnosis. However, blood culture and sensitivity are still considered the gold standard due to their widespread availability and reliability.","reference":"Dow lecture slides. Infectious module. Subject: Pediatrics, Topic: Enteric fever in children, Sub-topic: Laboratory diagnosis of typhoid.","responses":[{"text":"Widal Test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polymerase Chain Reaction (PCR)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood culture and sensitivity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Typhi dot","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete Blood Count (CBC)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22544,"text":"Which of the following is the first choice drug for the treatment of enteric fever?","explanation":"**Ceftriaxone** is considered the first-choice antibiotic for the treatment of **enteric fever**, especially in areas with a high prevalence of antibiotic resistance. It is highly effective against *Salmonella typhi* and *Salmonella paratyphi - the causative agents of typhoid and paratyphoid fevers.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nTetracycline antibiotics have been used in the past for the treatment of enteric fever. However, due to increasing antibiotic resistance, they are no longer recommended as first-line treatment in many regions.\r\n\r\nTrimethoprim alone is not typically used as the first-choice drug for enteric fever.\r\n\r\nErythromycin is not commonly used as the first-choice treatment for enteric fever. It may have a role in cases of mild infection or in individuals allergic to other antibiotics.\r\n\r\nChloramphenicol was once a commonly used antibiotic for enteric fever. However, due to the development of resistance and potential side effects, it is no longer the first-line choice in many regions.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 904.","responses":[{"text":"Trimethoprim","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetracycline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ceftriaxone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythromycin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chloramphenicol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22546,"text":"Which of the following is the drug of choice for a cestode infestation?","explanation":"**Cestodes**, commonly known as tapeworms, are parasitic flatworms that can infest the human gastrointestinal tract. **Praziquantel** is highly effective against a wide range of cestodes. It works by causing muscle contractions and paralysis in the tapeworm, which allows it to be expelled from the intestine.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nNiclosamide is another anthelmintic drug used to treat tapeworm infections but is generally considered a second-line treatment compared to praziquantel.\r\n\r\n\r\nIvermectin is mainly used to treat nematode (roundworm) infections.\r\n\r\nCarbamazepine is an anticonvulsant medication and is not used to treat cestode infestations.\r\n\r\nAlbendazole is an anthelmintic drug that is effective against both nematode and cestode infections. While it can be used to treat cestode infestations, praziquantel is usually preferred for its specific efficacy against tapeworms.","reference":"Whalen K, Finkel R, Panavelil TA. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 6th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2015: 562.","responses":[{"text":"Carbamizapine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ivermectin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Niclosamide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albendazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Praziquantal","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22547,"text":"Which of the following is a protease inhibitor used in combination for treatment of HIV?","explanation":"**Protease inhibitors** are a class of antiretroviral drugs used in the treatment of HIV. **Indinavir** is one of the protease inhibitors commonly used in combination therapy for HIV. It works by inhibiting the protease enzyme, which is essential for the replication of HIV.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nTenofovir is a nucleotide reverse transcriptase inhibitor (NRTI).\r\n\r\nEfavirenz is a non-nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitor (NNRTI).\r\n\r\nRaltegravir is an integrase strand transfer inhibitor (INSTI).\r\n\r\nEtravirine is another non-nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitor (NNRTI).","reference":"Whalen K, Finkel R, Panavelil TA. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 6th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2015: 568.","responses":[{"text":"Efavirenz","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tenofovir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Etravirine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Raltegravir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Indinavir","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22548,"text":"Which of the following statements is correct about anti-staphylococcal antibiotics?","explanation":"Anti-staphylococcal antibiotics like oxacillin, nafcillin, and dicloxacillin are specifically designed to resist inactivation by the enzyme penicillinase (beta-lactamase) produced by some staphylococcus bacteria. This resistance allows them to remain effective against penicillinase-producing staphylococcus strains.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nExtended spectrum typically refers to antibiotics that have a broader spectrum of activity, but it is not specific to anti-staphylococcal antibiotics.\r\n\r\nBroad-spectrum antibiotics are effective against a wide range of bacteria, including both Gram-positive and Gram-negative species. Anti-staphylococcal antibiotics are more narrow in their spectrum of activity, primarily targeting Gram-positive bacteria, especially Staphylococcus species.\r\n\r\nPenicillinase-sensitive implies that antibiotics are susceptible to inactivation by penicillinase, which is not the case for anti-staphylococcal antibiotics.\r\n\r\nAnti-staphylococcal antibiotics can be either natural or synthetic.","reference":"Whalen K, Finkel R, Panavelil TA. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 6th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2015: 485.","responses":[{"text":"Are synthetic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Penicillinase-sensitive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extended spectrum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Penicillinase-resistant","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Broad spectrum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22549,"text":"A 27-year-old nursing mother is diagnosed as suffering from genital herpes. She has a history of this viral infection. Previously, she responded to a drug used topically. Which drug to be used orally is most likely to be prescribed at this time?","explanation":"**Valacyclovir** is often the preferred choice for oral treatment of **recurrent genital herpes** due to its efficacy, ease of dosing, and safety profile, especially in patients who have a history of responding well to antiviral therapy. It is the prodrug of acyclovir, meaning it is converted to acyclovir in the body.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nTrifluridine is an antiviral medication, but it is usually used topically for conditions like herpes keratitis (eye infection) and not typically for genital herpes.\r\n\r\nRitonavir is an antiretroviral medication used to treat HIV, not herpes simplex virus infections.\r\n\r\nFoscarnet is an antiviral medication used for the treatment of various viral infections, including herpes, but it is generally reserved for cases of acyclovir-resistant herpes infections due to its potential for side effects.\r\n\r\nAmantadine is an antiviral medication used to treat influenza A infections and is not a standard treatment for genital herpes.","reference":"Whalen K, Finkel R, Panavelil TA. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 6th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2015: 567, 572.","responses":[{"text":"Amantadine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Foscarnet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ritonavir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Valacyclovir","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Trifluridine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22550,"text":"A patient with AIDS has a CD4 count of 45/µL. He is being maintained on a 3-drug regimen of indinavir, didanosine, and zidovudine. Which of the following drugs may cause an episode of acute pancreatitis?","explanation":"**Acute pancreatitis** is a known side effect of **didanosine**, which is a nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitor (NRTI) commonly used in the treatment of HIV infection, including in patients with AIDS. The risk of developing acute pancreatitis with didanosine is increased in patients with low CD4 counts.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nRitonavir is a protease inhibitor and is not typically associated with acute pancreatitis.\r\n\r\nZidovudine is another NRTI used in HIV treatment but is not typically associated with acute pancreatitis.\r\n\r\nAcyclovir is an antiviral medication used to treat herpes virus infections and is not known to cause acute pancreatitis.\r\n\r\nKetoconazole is an antifungal medication and is not commonly associated with acute pancreatitis.","reference":"Whalen K, Finkel R, Panavelil TA. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 6th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2015: 576.","responses":[{"text":"Zidovudine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Didanosine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acyclovir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ketoconazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ritonavir","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22551,"text":"A premature neonate suffered respiratory distress and was given an antibiotic 100 mg/kg/day orally. Over the next two days, his condition worsened. He became dull, stopped feeding, and developed abdominal distention, and an ashen grey appearance. Which is the most likely antibiotic given to him?","explanation":"**Chloramphenicol** is known to cause **gray baby syndrome**, particularly in premature neonates. Neonates, especially premature ones, have immature liver function and thus a reduced ability to metabolize and excrete chloramphenicol. This leads to drug accumulation, causing symptoms like abdominal distention, vomiting, refusal to feed, progressive cyanosis, and an ashen-gray color of the skin, as described in the scenario.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile erythromycin can cause gastrointestinal disturbances, it is not typically associated with severe symptoms of gray baby syndrome.\r\n\r\nAmpicillin is a commonly used antibiotic in neonates and is generally well-tolerated. \r\n\r\nMinocycline is not typically used in neonates. It can cause discoloration of teeth and bone issues in children.\r\n\r\nCiprofloxacin is not commonly used in neonates due to concerns about its effects on bone and cartilage growth.","reference":"Whalen K, Finkel R, Panavelil TA. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 6th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2015: 509.","responses":[{"text":"Erythromycin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chloramphenicol","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ciprofloxacin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ampicillin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Minocycline","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22552,"text":"An 8-year-old child presented with brownish discolored and deformed anterior teeth. He has a history of taking an antibiotic about 4 years earlier. Which antibiotic could be responsible for the condition?","explanation":"Tetracycline antibiotics, when taken during tooth development - typically during pregnancy or in children under the age of 8 - can lead to permanent discoloration and deformities of teeth. This condition is known as \"**tetracycline staining**.\" The teeth often appear brownish or yellowish and can have a mottled or striped appearance. \r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nErythromycin,  chloramphenicol, gentamicin, and ampicillin are not associated with tooth discoloration or deformities when taken during tooth development.","reference":"Whalen K, Finkel R, Panavelil TA. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 6th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2015: 502.","responses":[{"text":"Chloramphenicol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gentamicin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ampicillin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetracycline","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythromycin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22554,"text":"Which enzymes are the target for the quinolone antibacterial agents?","explanation":"**Quinolone** antibiotics, such as ciprofloxacin and levofloxacin, target bacterial **topoisomerases**, specifically DNA gyrase and topoisomerase IV. These enzymes are essential for the replication and maintenance of bacterial DNA.\r\n\r\nBy inhibiting the activity of DNA gyrase and topoisomerase IV, quinolones disrupt the bacterial DNA replication process, leading to DNA strand breaks and ultimately bacterial cell death.","reference":"Whalen K, Finkel R, Panavelil TA. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 6th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2015: 513.","responses":[{"text":"Transpeptidases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyclases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kinases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Topoisomerases","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Proteases","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22555,"text":"Which fluoroquinolone is highly active against Mycobacterium leprae and is being used in alternative multidrug therapy regimens?","explanation":"***Mycobacterium leprae*** is the bacterium responsible for leprosy (Hansen disease). **Ofloxacin** is known for its potent activity against Mycobacterium leprae and is an essential component of alternative multidrug therapy regimens used for the treatment of leprosy.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nNorfloxacin is a fluoroquinolone, but it is not typically used as the first-line treatment for leprosy. Ofloxacin is preferred.\r\n\r\nLomefloxacin is another fluoroquinolone, but it is not commonly used for treating leprosy.\r\n\r\nWhile levofloxacin is a fluoroquinolone with broad-spectrum antibacterial activity, ofloxacin is more commonly used for leprosy.\r\n\r\nCiprofloxacin is another fluoroquinolone, but it is not the first choice for treating leprosy.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Infectious module, Subject: Microbiology; Topic: Atypical Mycobacteria and Leprosy; Sub-topic: Treatment and Management.","responses":[{"text":"Ciprofloxacin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Levofloxacin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ofloxacin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lomefloxacin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Norfloxacin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22561,"text":"A 35-year-old male presented to the outpatient department with a prolonged history of fever and weight loss. On clinical examination, there is lymphadenopathy and hepatosplenomegaly. Complete blood count (CBC) shows pancytopenia. He is suspected of visceral leishmaniasis. Which of the following investigations is used for definitive diagnosis of visceral leishmaniasis?","explanation":"Identification of **amastigote** in macrophages in tissue samples is the most definitive diagnostic method for **visceral leishmaniasis**. A biopsy of the bone marrow, spleen, or lymph nodes is typically performed, and amastigotes (intracellular forms of the parasite) are identified within macrophages in these tissue samples. This provides a direct confirmation of the disease.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile blood culture can be useful for diagnosing some infections, it is not the primary method for diagnosing visceral leishmaniasis. The parasite may not always be present in the bloodstream, making blood culture less reliable for this specific diagnosis.\r\n\r\nSerology involves testing for antibodies against the *Leishmania* parasite. While serological tests can be helpful, they are not as specific as identifying the actual parasite in tissue samples and may yield false positives or negatives in some cases.\r\n\r\nAntigen-based rapid tests are often used as a screening tool for leishmaniasis.\r\n\r\nMolecular tests like polymerase chain reaction (PCR) can be used to detect the DNA of the *Leishmania* parasite. While they can be sensitive and specific, they are not always readily available in all healthcare settings, and the identification of amastigotes in tissue samples remains the gold standard for diagnosis.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 282.","responses":[{"text":"Molecular test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antigen based rapid test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Identification of amastigote in macrophages in tissue sample","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood culture","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22562,"text":"A 16-year-old male presents to the outpatient department with a three-day history of high-grade fever, flu, itchy red eyes, and rashes all over the body. On examination, the physician found Kolpik spots in the oral cavity and a maculopapular rash scattered all over the body. The most likely diagnosis will be?","explanation":"**Measles** is characterized by a high-grade fever, flu-like symptoms, itchy red eyes (conjunctivitis), and a maculopapular rash that typically starts on the face and spreads to cover the entire body. The presence of **Koplik spots** in the oral cavity is a classic finding in measles. These spots are small white or grayish-blue spots on the inside of the cheeks and are pathognomonic for measles.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nMumps presents with fever and swollen salivary glands, particularly the parotid gland.\r\n\r\nAtopic dermatitis is a chronic inflammatory skin condition characterized by itching and eczematous skin changes.\r\n\r\nRubella, also known as German measles, can present with a rash and flu-like symptoms but is not associated with Koplik spots.\r\n\r\nChickenpox presents with a vesicular rash, not a maculopapular rash. It can lead to flu-like symptoms but lacks Koplik spots.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 236.","responses":[{"text":"Rubella","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mumps","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Measles","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chickenpox","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atopic dermatitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22563,"text":"A 50-year-old female while cleaning her home sustained a rusty metal injury on her right finger. She is very cautious and came to seek treatment at the emergency department. You have washed her wound with normal saline and dressed it. Which of the following infections she is at risk of acquiring?","explanation":"***Clostridium tetani*** is responsible for causing tetanus. Tetanus spores are commonly found in soil and can enter the body through wounds, especially those contaminated with soil, rust, or foreign bodies. **Rusty metal injuries** are considered high-risk for tetanus if the patient's tetanus vaccination is not up to date. The bacterium produces a neurotoxin that leads to muscle stiffness and spasms, potentially progressing to life-threatening complications.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n*Clostridium perfringens* is associated with gas gangrene, a severe soft tissue infection. While it can be found in wounds, it is less commonly associated with rusty metal injuries and is more frequently linked to deep puncture wounds and injuries with significant tissue damage.\r\n\r\n*Clostridium difficile* is responsible for causing antibiotic-associated diarrhea and colitis. It is not typically associated with injuries like rusty metal punctures.\r\n\r\n*Clostridium botulinum* produces botulinum toxin, which causes botulism. Botulism is primarily associated with the ingestion of contaminated food.\r\n\r\n*Clostridium sordellii* is associated with infections such as endometritis and toxic shock syndrome. It is not commonly linked to rusty metal injuries.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 1125.","responses":[{"text":"Clostridium sordelli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium botulinum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium perfringens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium difficile","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium tetani","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22564,"text":"A 20-year-old college student presented to the medical specialist with complaints of fever, extra-orbital pain, and fatigue for one week. On examination, the patient is febrile and has a macular skin rash. The lab results reveal a Hb of 11 g/dl, a TLC of 3500 cells/dl, a platelet count of 50,000, and an increased hematocrit. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Dengue fever** is a mosquito-borne viral infection that often presents with fever, headache, retro-orbital pain, and a macular skin rash. The hematologic findings in dengue fever can include thrombocytopenia, increased hematocrit, and sometimes anemia. This combination of symptoms and laboratory findings is characteristic of dengue fever.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nLeptospira is associated with a disease called leptospirosis. While leptospirosis can also present with fever and skin rash, it is not typically associated with thrombocytopenia and hemoconcentration to the extent seen in dengue fever.\r\n\r\nIdiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP) primarily presents with isolated thrombocytopenia and may not have the associated symptoms of fever, extra-orbital pain, or skin rash seen in this case.\r\n\r\nMalaria may cause fever, but it usually presents with symptoms like chills, rigors, and cyclical fever patterns. Thrombocytopenia and hemoconcentration are not typically the hallmark findings in malaria.\r\n\r\nYellow fever can cause fever and jaundice, but it is not typically associated with the combination of symptoms and laboratory findings mentioned in the case, such as extra-orbital pain, macular skin rash, and a platelet count as low as 50,000.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 243-244.","responses":[{"text":"Yellow fever","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dengue fever","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leptospira","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malaria","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22565,"text":"A 35-year-old man presented to the skin specialist with complaints of skin lesions on his face and arms for six months. The lesions are hypopigmented and lack sensation. On examination, the skin over the brows and ears has thickened, and there are nodules on the face. He was diagnosed as having leprosy. Which of the following statements is correct?","explanation":"The **lepromin test** is used to determine the type of leprosy and the patient's immune response to *Mycobacterium leprae*. It is positive in **tuberculoid leprosy**, which is associated with a strong cell-mediated immune response that limits the spread of the disease. In tuberculoid leprosy, the skin lesions are fewer and well-demarcated, and there is significant nerve involvement leading to loss of sensation in the affected areas.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe tuberculin skin test is used for diagnosing tuberculosis, caused by *Mycobacterium tuberculosis*, not for leprosy.\r\n\r\nThe clinical presentation described in the question is indeed classical for leprosy, particularly for the lepromatous form, which is characterized by widespread skin lesions, nodules, and thickening of the skin over certain areas.\r\n\r\nIn lepromatous leprosy, the lepromin skin test is usually negative. This form of leprosy represents a weak cell-mediated immune response, leading to widespread, poorly defined lesions without significant nerve damage initially.\r\n\r\nCell-mediated immunity plays a crucial role in the pathogenesis of leprosy. In tuberculoid leprosy, there is a strong cell-mediated response with the formation of granulomas. In lepromatous leprosy, the cell-mediated response is weak, and granulomas are less organized or absent.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 267-268.","responses":[{"text":"There is no role for cell-mediated immunity, but granulomas are usually absent","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lepromin skin testing is positive in lepromatous types of leprosy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Its clinical presentation is not classical","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The lepromin skin test is positive in the tuberculoid type of leprosy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberculin skin test is positive for any type of leprosy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22566,"text":"A 19-year-old woman presented to the emergency department after complaining of abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting for 2 hours. Her abdominal pain is sudden, and she has no history of fever or diarrhea. She had taken fried rice, grilled chicken, and vegetables for lunch five hours before at a local restaurant. What is the most likely mechanism responsible for the symptoms?","explanation":"Sudden abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting within a short period after consuming a meal are suggestive of **food poisoning**. Food poisoning can occur when individuals ingest food that is contaminated with **preformed toxins** produced by bacteria. In this case, the patient ate fried rice, grilled chicken, and vegetables from a local restaurant, which might have been contaminated.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe rapid onset of symptoms within 2 hours after the meal suggests that the symptoms are not due to bacteria invading the small or large intestine and causing infection.\r\n\r\nThe symptoms' rapid onset does not align with the time needed for bacteria to proliferate and produce toxins.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 262.","responses":[{"text":"Bacterial invasion of the small intestine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malabsorption by bacterial overgrowth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proliferation with subsequent production of toxins by bacteria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacterial invasion of the large intestine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ingestion of preformed toxins","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22567,"text":"A 36-year-old man presented to the emergency room with complaints of fever and mild abdominal pain for 3 days. On examination, he is febrile (103°F) with jaundice and a palpable spleen. Plasmodium falciparum trophozoites are visible in the peripheral film. In cases of uncomplicated falciparum malaria, which treatment is recommended?","explanation":"**Artemether** and **lumefantrine** are both effective against *Plasmodium falciparum* and are commonly used in combination as a first-line treatment for uncomplicated cases of falciparum malaria.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nPrimaquine is used to treat relapsing forms of malaria caused by *Plasmodium vivax* and *Plasmodium ovale*.\r\n\r\nWhile artemether is effective against falciparum malaria, proguanil is not typically used for falciparum malaria.\r\n\r\nChloroquine is no longer the recommended treatment for falciparum malaria in most regions due to widespread drug resistance.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 128.","responses":[{"text":"Artemether plus lumifantrine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Primaquine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Artemether plus proguanil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chloroquine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Quinine and doxycycline","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22568,"text":"A 24-year-old man from Baluchistan presented to the dermatology clinic complaining of an erythematous nodule in his right arm that had been bothering him for a month. There are no such lesions located on the ears, lips, or oral mucosa. The systemic review was unremarkable. The histopathology of the lesion shows granulomatous inflammation in the dermis and peripherally located amastigotes. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Cutaneous leishmaniasis** typically presents as erythematous nodules or ulcers on the skin, and it is caused by the protozoa *Leishmania*. The presence of granulomatous inflammation in the dermis and the identification of **amastigotes** in histopathology are characteristic findings in cutaneous leishmaniasis. \r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nVisceral leishmaniasis primarily affects internal organs such as the spleen, liver, and bone marrow. It does not typically present with erythematous nodules on the skin.\r\n\r\nLeprosy can have various dermatological manifestations, but it is characterized by skin lesions that are hypopigmented, anesthetic, and often involve cooler areas of the body. \r\n\r\nMucocutaneous leprosy typically involves both skin and mucous membranes, such as the oral mucosa. The absence of oral mucosal involvement in this case makes mucocutaneous leprosy less likely.\r\n\r\nTuberculosis can cause cutaneous manifestations, but the presence of amastigotes in the histopathology is not consistent with tuberculosis.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 285.","responses":[{"text":"Tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Visceral leishmaniasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cutaneous leishmaniasis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Leprosy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mucocutaneous leprosy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22572,"text":"A 25-year-old male presented with fever and abdominal pain. His illness started with low-grade fever and decreased appetite. He has been unwell for the past 7 days and has per rectal bleeding for the last 2 days. Initially, he took per ciprofloxacin for 3 days followed by oral cefixime and azithromycin for 4 days. He was started on intravenous (IV) ceftriaxone. What is the most appropriate diagnostic test?","explanation":"Symptoms such as fever, abdominal pain, decreased appetite, and per rectal bleeding along with the history of antibiotic use, raise suspicion of an infectious cause, particularly a gastrointestinal infection. In such cases, obtaining a stool culture is the most appropriate diagnostic test to identify the causative organism responsible for the gastrointestinal infection.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nBone marrow culture is typically used to diagnose conditions such as hematological malignancies or certain systemic infections, but it is not the first-line investigation in this case.\r\n\r\nWhile a rectal swab can be useful for identifying certain pathogens, a stool culture is a more comprehensive test to evaluate the presence of various bacteria and parasites in the gastrointestinal tract. \r\n\r\nBlood cultures are essential for diagnosing systemic bloodstream infections, but in this case, the primary concern is a gastrointestinal infection with per rectal bleeding. A stool culture is more specific for identifying the pathogens causing gastrointestinal symptoms.\r\n\r\nWhile a complete blood count (CBC) with peripheral smear can provide valuable information about the patient's overall health, it is not the most specific test for identifying the causative agent of gastrointestinal symptoms and per rectal bleeding.","reference":"(1) Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 265.\r\n\r\n(2) Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 153.","responses":[{"text":"Stool culture","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood culture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone marrow culture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rectal swab for culture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete blood picture with peripheral film","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

export default a